Here is a sample C++ function which calculates the linear regression of a vector of 2-d points:

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <utility>

using namespace std;

pair<double, double> linearRegression(vector<pair<double, double>> points) {
    double n = points.size();
    double sum_x = 0.0, sum_y = 0.0, sum_x2 = 0.0, sum_xy = 0.0;
    for (auto p : points) {
        sum_x += p.first;
        sum_y += p.second;
        sum_x2 += p.first * p.first;
        sum_xy += p.first * p.second;
    }
    double slope = (n * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / (n * sum_x2 - sum_x * sum_x);
    double intercept = (sum_y - slope * sum_x) / n;
    return {slope, intercept};
}
```

The function takes in a vector of pairs, representing the 2-d points. It then loops through each point, accumulating the sum of the x-values, y-values, squared x-values, and product of x and y. The slope and intercept of the linear regression are then calculated using those accumulated sums, and returned as a pair.

